summary.seg: The manuscript contains a Greek philosophical miscellany, comprising treatises and extracts mainly deriving from Aristotle. It is composed of three parts copied around the same time, two of which were written by the same scribe Nikolaos Sekoundinos (1402-1464). A colophon to one of them dates and locates its production to Florence in 1441. Nikolaos (also known as Nicolaus Secundinus, Nicholaus Secundinus, or Niccolò Sagundino) came from Negroponte (Euboea) and moved to Italy in 1438. Because of his good knowledge of Greek and Latin, he was an interpreter at the Council of Florence. He also served as a papal secretary for some years. He was interested in the Plato-Aristotle controversy of the period, taking a similar position to Cardinal Bessarion as a Platonist not really hostile to Aristotle.

foliation.p: Two foliations: the newer one, in pencil in Arabic numerals in the top right-hand corner, recto (ff. 1r-123r), includes the parchment leaves at the beginning as f. 1r in the count, but balances out f. 114r with the older foliation (in brown ink in Arabic numerals in the top right-hand corner, recto) covering only the paper leaves, since it omits "113". The 1856 catalogue refers to the older foliation.

condition.p: In fair condition; yellowed pages with some spots.

binding.p: Reversed skin binding with blind embossing reused from a previous boards (probably 16th or 17th century). Leather strip with tooled title from previous binding is glued to the left pastedown. Title (Miscellanea Graeca Philosophia) and shelfmark tooled in gold on spine. Repaired in October 1968, by Gray (Cambridge bookbinder), as noted on f. i recto

provenance.p: Owned by the Venitian scholar Niccolò Leonico Tomeo (1456?-1531?) Tomeo, Niccolò Leonico, 1456?-1531? who left some notes (ff. 241r, 260r, 263v) and some leafed twigs as page markers (e.g. f. 112v and f. 327v).

It later entered into the collection of John Moore (1646-1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 . The manuscript is neither listed in
Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697) nor in the handwritten supplementary list of Moore's manuscripts, now CUL MS Oo.7.50.2, compiled by Thomas Tanner after the publication of Bernard's catalogue, but a note on f. 1r states Late Bp of Elys MSS. lent to Mr. Dechaire for Mr. Pearse of Edmund Hall. The manuscript is also listed in the old catalogue of Parris-Whisson CUL MS Oo.7.53, f. 20r.

The manuscript was probably previously owned by Jean-Baptiste Hautin (1580?-1640) Haultin, Jean-Baptiste, approximately 1580-1640 , whose collection partially passed to Moore. On f. 1v remains a short title in French: Receuil.

history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1715 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 . The royal bookplate engraved by John Pine (1690-1756) in 1736 remains on left pastedown.

recordHist.source: Description (2019) draws on A catalogue of the Manuscripts preserved in the Library of the University of Cambridge, vol. 1, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1856, p. 217-225 and J. Wiesner's record in P. Moraux, Aristoteles Graecus, Walter De Gruyter, Berlin-New York, 1976, pp. 99-103.

availability.p: Entry to read in the Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.

support.material: ff. 12r-291v Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermark: Greek cross in a circle ( 40 40 ) in the gutter comparable to Briquet, Croix grecque dans un cercle 5575 . Dated to 1456.

collation.p: This part consists of 28 quinions: quires 2-2910 ff. 12r-291v.
collation.catchwords: Horizontal catchwords in the hand of the scribe from f. 21v to 281v.
collation.signatures: Quire signature in Arabic numerals on the first recto, lower margin from f. 12r (2) to f. 282r (29). Only at the beginning is there a Latin letter count on the last verso and the first recto, lower margin of ff. 11v, 12r (a) to ff. 31v, 32r (c).

condition.p: In fair condition; yellowed pages with some spots. The corners of the book block are worn and rounded.

handNote.p: This part was copied by Nikolaos Sekoundinos Sekoundinos, Nikolaos, 1402-1464? (PLP 25106, RGK I 316), active in the mid-15th century, in a scholarly-calligraphical minuscule script in brown ink.
Slanting slightly to the right, Sekoundinos' hand shows cursive-like ductus without marked variation in letter size. Ligatures and abbreviations are rare, common and very clear.

His script is characterized by the bilobate beta; minuscule theta widely open, along with the closed shape; pi with different eyelets and the ligatures of ἐπί. Breathings are curved; accents join to letters or breathings but without consistency.

history.origin: The copyist left a date in the third part of the manuscript (1441); the watermarks of the second part suggest that this was written after the third, around 1456.
